{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:02:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16843"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16843"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.57,0.29,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9533"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67259"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9533"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52711"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"1793"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"3902"},{"type":"tags","id":"4188"},{"type":"tags","id":"9331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12802"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22515"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67259"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of increasing abdominal distension, early satiety, and constipation. She has lost 5 kg in weight despite appearing more bloated. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She went through menopause at age 51.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired. Her vital signs are within normal limits. Her abdomen is distended with shifting dullness. There is a firm, irregular mass palpable in the left lower quadrant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 108 g/L (115-165)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 7.2 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EPlatelet count: 350 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003ESodium: 138 mmol/L (135-145)\u003Cbr /\u003EPotassium: 4.2 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlbumin: 38 g/L (35-50)\u003Cbr /\u003EAlkaline phosphatase: 85 U/L (30-110)\u003Cbr /\u003EGamma-GT: 32 U/L (5-35)\u003Cbr /\u003EALT: 25 U/L (5-35)\u003Cbr /\u003EBilirubin: 12 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003Cbr /\u003ECA-125: 850 U/mL (0-35)\u003Cbr /\u003ECEA: 2.5 ng/mL (0-4.7)\u003Cbr /\u003ECA 19-9: 45 U/mL (0-37)\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECT scan of the chest shows no evidence of metastatic disease. CT scan of the abdomen and pelvis shows bilateral complex ovarian masses, omental caking, moderate ascites, and multiple peritoneal deposits throughout the abdomen and pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely stage of this patient\u0027s ovarian cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Stage IIc","Stage III","Stage IV","Stage I","Stage II"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with clinical and radiological features of advanced ovarian cancer. The presence of omental caking, peritoneal deposits throughout the abdomen, and ascites are characteristic findings in advanced disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage III\u003C/strong\u003E ovarian cancer is defined by tumour involving one or both ovaries with cytologically or histologically confirmed spread to the peritoneum outside the pelvis and/or metastasis to the retroperitoneal lymph nodes. The CT findings of omental caking and peritoneal deposits throughout the abdomen are diagnostic of stage III disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage I\u003C/strong\u003E disease is confined to the ovaries or fallopian tubes, which is clearly not the case here given the extensive intra-abdominal spread.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage II\u003C/strong\u003E disease involves extension or metastasis to extraovarian pelvic organs (e.g., uterus, fallopian tubes, bladder, sigmoid colon, or rectum). This patient\u0027s disease extends beyond the pelvis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage IIc\u003C/strong\u003E is an outdated classification that is no longer used in current staging systems. The current FIGO staging system has simplified stage II disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStage IV\u003C/strong\u003E disease involves distant metastasis beyond the peritoneal cavity. The normal chest CT and liver function tests, along with the absence of extra-abdominal metastases on imaging, exclude stage IV disease at this stage. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe markedly elevated CA-125 is consistent with, but not diagnostic of, advanced disease. The combination of bilateral ovarian masses, omental caking, peritoneal deposits, and ascites is characteristic of advanced epithelial ovarian cancer.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Advanced ovarian cancer commonly presents with non-specific symptoms including abdominal distension, early satiety, and changes in bowel habits.","The presence of omental caking, ascites, and peritoneal deposits on CT indicates stage III ovarian cancer.","CA-125 is typically markedly elevated in advanced epithelial ovarian cancer but is not specific for staging."],"references":["Berek JS, Renz M, Kehoe S, Kumar L, Friedlander M. Cancer of the ovary, fallopian tube, and peritoneum: 2021 update. Int J Gynaecol Obstet. 2021 Oct;155 Suppl 1(Suppl 1):61-85. doi: 10.1002/ijgo.13878. PMID: 34669199; PMCID: PMC9298325."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52711"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16843"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52711","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52711"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-04T11:05:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T11:06:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9533"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67259"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"da